				\begin{document}$${\Phi }_{\mathrm{PSII}} = a \ast {\mathrm{exp}}(I \ast b)$$\end{document}ΦPSII=a*exp(I*b)where I is the irradiance, a is a normalization constant, and b is the rate constant which characterizes how rapidly ΦPSII declines with increasing I. Eq. (8) was fitted to the ΦPSII data using a no-linear mixed model including random effects by biological replicate on each parameter and “selection environment” as a fixed factor. Model output was then used to calculate ΦPSII at the light intensity that samples would have experienced in the incubators (i.e., ~ 100 µmol quanta m−2 s−1). Model selection then proceeded as described above for P and R data. Detailed model output and model selection data are available in Supplementary Table 9 where nomenclature and acronyms are as given here (see also Supplementary Figure 3).
